##Huachuang capital Xiong Weiming: 2020, venture opportunities where?

Micro-signal, Rancaijing

A feature presentation, a daily in depth report, redefines the innovation economy.

Original by ran CAIJING

By Yana Meng

Editor | Zhou Changfan

The past two years, the capital market investment slowdown, venture capital situation overall downturn, AI industry also ushered in the capital cold winter.

On the one hand, companies look forward to early financing to continue the application-level technology landing; on the other hand, the early investors want to exit the profit.

But artificial intelligence in the practical application of far less than expected, "AI bubble burst theory" clamor. In the view of Huachuang capital Xiong Weiming, every new field will be accompanied by a so-called bubble, but the bubble is not meaningless, such as it promotes the industry's talent training.

In addition, the application of artificial intelligence in the medical field is also beginning to fall, beginning to focus on the field of life sciences pharmaceutical. Xiong Weiming gave advice to entrepreneurs, if you want to start a business in this area, from the pharmaceutical sector upstream and downstream and peripheral cut, will have an advantage.

Currently affected by the epidemic, many small and medium-sized enterprises are also facing a cash flow crisis.

"If you're pessimistic, you're probably not going to see any cash flow in six months. In this case, entrepreneurs need to make adjustments. If the enterprise has too little money to turn around or change, it is better to reduce production and hibernate. If there is still some money to support seven or eight months, we can try something new,"Xiong said.

On February 27, CNFC held an online salon with the theme focused on Ai Industry. Huachuang capital partner Xiong Weiming, Kuangshi Vice President Xie Yinan, and Kuaicang intelligence co-founder Sun Yu shared the theme, and He Shulong, the editor-in-chief of finance and economics, made a dialogue.

Here is Xiong Weiming's detailed sharing on the Financial Salon:

What is the era after the Internet?

We lack consensus

Compared with 2003, Zhu Min, Dean of the National Institute of Finance at Tsinghua University, said in a speech a few days ago that the two quarters could cause about $1.38 trillion in direct losses, mostly from offline businesses. Any business that delivers part of its business offline will be seriously affected during this period, which will be significantly higher than in 2003 due to the significant increase in the size and urbanisation of our economy.

According to the latest forecast by the Economist Intelligence Unit, China's GDP growth rate will peak at around 4.5% in 2020. But relative to the size of the country's entire tier one hundred trillion economy, the figure is still optimistic.

Compared with 2003 SARS period, the structure of China's GDP growth has changed a lot. Since 2018, the country has made structural changes and changed its financial policies. But the market has encountered a variety of uncertain factors, financial policy on the brake on many small and medium-sized enterprises suffered a wave of impact, sino-us trade negotiations, many export-oriented enterprises affected; The new crown pneumonia outbreak has left some local consumer businesses with a lot to lose.

In late 2019, Meituan Wang Xing said, "2019 was the worst year of the past decade, but the best year of the next decade. " In fact, in 2019, primary market investment has been slowing. In addition to the big changes in financial policy, the fundamentals are also changing a lot. From a technical point of view, I summarize three points:

First, global consumption of the Internet has reached a bottleneck. With the exception of Africa, where 2 billion young people still face a whole new state of affairs without infrastructure in place.

Consumer Internet penetration is already very high in the two most populous countries, China and the United States. From some macro-data, China has ushered in the development of a new inflection point. Up to now, China's online population has reached 1.1 billion, the retail market has reached about 5.6 trillion US dollars, has surpassed the United States. In addition, China's e-commerce market more than 1 trillion US dollars, has become the world's largest e-commerce market.

Second, the fund-raising cycle is lengthening. With the quantitative easing policy in 2009, countries increased liquidity, 2013 began the market ushered in a new fund-raising cycle. This period is very similar to the period of high growth of small and medium-sized banks in the United States. At its peak, there were about 140,000 small and medium-sized banks in the United States, eventually merging into 8,000 to 9,000. During that time, the U.S. government introduced federal insurance policies to protect the deposits of these small and medium-sized bank depositors. The wave of crowdfunding platforms that we experienced later, the lowering of the barriers to angel investing, the P2P, and microfinance markets, was very much like the United States of that period. But in essence, this phenomenon is in fact the capital liquidity overflow, the performance of excess liquidity.

In 2017, China registered as many as 30,000 funds, but the number began to decline significantly in 2018. In 2018, RMB fund raising was basically at a standstill. In the second half of 2019, fund raising started to show some improvement, but it was still far from the previous years. But for truly professional early-stage investors, now is the perfect time to focus more on the long-term.

In addition, in terms of fund-raising cycle, affected by sino-us trade relations, for some large-scale capital, especially LP pension fund-related direction of the institutions, fund-raising cycle may be affected.

Third, we are in an era of a global lack of consensus on infrastructure upgrading.

In the late 1990s, when the Internet was just born, there was a consensus that the Internet was the future. In 2001, the high point of the Internet came to an end, and the community of the Internet began to emerge. FACEBOOK was founded in 2004, and the era of e commerce began. Then came all sorts of games and subscription services. In 2007, the first iPhone was introduced, and in 2014 and 2015, the entire mobile internet and smartphones became ubiquitous.

Everyone's consensus also from the Internet is the future, has become a "cloud" is the future, and then to the mobile Internet is the future.

In fact, what we're talking about now is that the Internet of things is also a part of the Internet, an extension of the Internet. As for what the Internet will be after, we actually have no particularly clear consensus. We've been talking about RFID since the early 2000s, but the technology is only slowly being implemented today.

Enterprise software, infrastructure, core technology

Top three startup opportunities right now

Whether there is an epidemic or not, here are three areas that would be good start-ups and investment opportunities.

First, enterprise software for small and medium enterprises. But I personally think startups are going to have a lot of challenges doing collaborative software, it's a big business by nature. Nail and Wechat are both P2P communication software with social attributes, and P2P communication software is generally a large factory to do things.

So, for small and medium-sized enterprises efficiency software may be more in some vertical industry, such as the catering industry. For the standard U. S. Restaurant Industry, our restaurant industry is still very small. For example, a new American restaurant APP, Toast, has been valued at more than $4 billion. But similar software in China is valued at hundreds of millions of dollars or even hundreds of millions of yuan. The reason is that the user's usage habits have not been completely changed, for example, payment habits, the speed of business deployment, etc. .

Second, infrastructure. The rapid development of mobile Internet and Internet of things has changed the business model of many Chinese enterprises. The latest annual report of China Merchants Bank shows that mobile banking and palm life apps add up to more than 85 million monthly live, a huge scale. By contrast, in the United States, Europe, Japan and other countries, the same financial services software, whether PC or mobile far less than China. Some Chinese companies are evolving into Internet companies.

In the process of evolution, enterprises often have a variety of needs, such as location function, identity authentication function, fingerprint recognition and facial recognition functions. These developments are a big trend for companies around the world. Our infrastructure is changing, for example, the database is changing, and the validation process for many things is changing. In these areas, China is very much ahead of the curve in innovation.

Third, core technology. Examples include semiconductor supply chains, life sciences, industrial intelligence, next-generation communications, and the aerospace industry. For a long time, China's investment in similar high-end manufacturing industry is very limited, but there are some advantages. At present, the world's largest enterprises represented by 3C are all in China, therefore, the corresponding supply chain of high-end manufacturing industry will move to China sooner or later.

Ai Pharmaceuticals is still focused on pharmaceuticals

It's important to get through it

In the last two years, there has been a lot of interest in the possibility of AI enabling life sciences, or healthcare, where vertical ai is more easily understood.

One of the earliest inspirations in the field of artificial intelligence was IBM Watson. But after the case of IBM Watson and MSK, there was no major company of any significant size. In fact, as Google Becomes Alphabet, it has started to deploy a variety of medical and life science related subsidiaries, and in that sense, Google could replace IBM, into one of the leading companies driven by natural language processing and computer vision.

Microsoft had already tried something before Google. Microsoft created a Vault to study how IT could be applied to health care, but that didn't happen. It turns out that the bigger the company, the more it doesn't have an advantage in the medical field. The most successful example of this is Flatiron Health, a new york-based start-up that was sold to Hoffmann-La Roche for $1.9 billion a few years ago.

Between 2014 and 2015, many entrepreneurs tried to start their own businesses in fields related to the iron iron, trying to make reading aids to help doctors. But the iron iron of the day had essentially replaced much of the doctor's reading.

Back then, a lot of people in China were chasing data from Google's lung nodules contest to start their own businesses. But the medical ecosystem in the US and China is not quite the same, and in the end most people find that these business directions copied from the US are not suitable for China. First of all, AI is no substitute for a doctor. Second, companies need to overcome many regulatory and commercial factors.

So, after going through changes in AI, life sciences, and medicine, we are turning our attention to the field of artificial intelligence in the pharmaceutical industry. Two publicly traded companies in this area in recent years, Schrödinger (NASDAQ: SDGR) and Black Diamond Nasdaq: BDTX, have opened up opportunities for many.

Typically, a drug takes about $1 billion, 10 years to develop, and with the help of Ai, that time could be shortened considerably.

On the other hand, AI is not a hot market, and it takes time to start a business in this area. Companies like Schrödinger, which has been in business for 30 years, had revenues of $60 million in 2018, and 25 other projects had to be completed in collaboration because of a lack of capital and energy. Black Diamond, by contrast, is growing faster, coming on the market in less than six years, but has so far produced only two preclinical drugs. So the industry is still waiting to see if AI can deliver the desired results.

It's also a challenge for entrepreneurs to stay the course. But using artificial intelligence to help develop new drugs is not new.

As early as October 1981, the cover of Fortune magazine had already reported that Merck & Co. was using a computer to do calculations that would help speed up the development of new drugs. But none of the drugs developed by AI have come to market yet.

In 2017, a paper in the journal Nature titled the Drugmakers'Galactic Travel Handbook noted that the global number of synthetic molecules has the potential to be around 10 to the 60th power, while our IPV6 currently only reaches 10 to the 32nd power, so, even though we're a lot better at math than we were in 1981, it's still not enough.

We've talked to a lot of scientists, and they think that the process of going from 0 to 1, Ai really helps, because it's very fast, but the process of going from 1 to 10, from 10 to 100, involves some human intervention, for example, with the help of chemists and biologists. So across the board, though, we expect that with the help of AI, computational chemistry can become the Excel of new drug discovery, using computational power to improve our design capabilities. But as it turns out, the focus of AI is still on pharmaceuticals.

For pharmaceutical companies, the ultimate value of the company depends on the pipeline of new drugs, pre-clinical conditions and target selection and so on. Therefore, from the entrepreneurial point of view, we think from the pharmaceutical sector upstream and downstream and peripheral cut, will have an advantage.

Because big companies often don't do new drug R & D, there's a huge opportunity if the startup has both AI capabilities and an understanding of the pharmaceutical industry.

Although there are more than 200 companies in the market, most of them are not Chinese companies. These companies include integrated AI companies like Kuang Shi, but many more are vertical AI companies. This is an area where you can't be bothered by giants, but because the big trends in this area are related to pharmaceuticals, it's up to the founders to make it work.

In fact, China is very competitive in AI, globally. Our algorithmic engineers have an advantage in math, physics, and chemistry, which means many young people can go a long way in AI. So at the moment, I think a lot of relevant entrepreneurs in China are hoping to seize this opportunity, with the help of artificial intelligence, to catch up with the pace of new drug development in Europe, the United States and Japan.

Dialogue Xiong Weiming:

The challenge for investment firms is to raise capital

The whole venture will be slow this year

Fuel Finance and Economics: under the epidemic situation, which projects of Huachuang capital investment have been more obvious impact, which instead ushered in the growth opportunities? What was the most difficult thing you heard about the project? What advice would you give to a project in trouble?

Xiong Weiming: All of our businesses involved in offline delivery have been affected, but many e-commerce related projects have seen a big increase in traffic, so it's a mixed blessing for us.

The growth opportunities will come from projects that involve offline scenarios. We have a company called kitchen. Because of the outbreak, everyone started to cook at home, adding a lot of new users to them, and the servers were overwhelmed, this is an unexpected contribution of the epidemic.

The biggest hurdle for companies, of course, is ensuring cash flow in the event of a pandemic. Many companies are financing a more conservative rhythm, affected by the epidemic, equivalent to the suspension of three to four months of cash flow. If you're pessimistic, you're probably not going to see any cash inflows for six months. In this case, the entrepreneur may need to make adjustments, if the enterprise money is too little, too late to turn around or change, as well as production reduction and hibernation, if the enterprise has some funds, can support seven or eight months, can do some new try.

Fuel Finance and Economics: YOU ARE A leading technology sector investment in China, has invested in projects involving private aviation, autopilot, etc. . For the investment in technology projects, what dimensions do you pay more attention to, what is your underlying thinking logic? Will there be a change in investment strategy in this direction after the outbreak?

Xiong Weiming: in cutting-edge technology, if we exclude the life sciences, actually our theme is very clear. Because life sciences is a very specialized field, think of it as an industry, a trillion dollar industry on a par with health care and finance.

One of our two themes revolves around China leading the world in some areas, such as commercial spaceflight. In Commercial Space, China is very technologically advanced, but with companies like Space x and Blue Origin, we are temporarily behind in the private sector. For example, in the field of AI, I think China's talent input based on AI mathematical calculation is very advantageous. Moreover, in some niche areas, such as computational science, where computing is a force driven field, computer science has a wide variety of opportunities.

Another big theme is communication-based areas. Communication in China has traditionally been weak. China has always been a downstream integrator of the supply chain, so whether we do base stations or personal communication devices, what we actually produce is often the final product. But because the final product is made in China, our upstream component capabilities are also improving. The semiconductor industry, for example, has been on this wave for two years.

So we think there's a good chance that China communications will be able to bring Chinese semiconductors.

Fuel Finance and Economics: What are the new challenges that the epidemic has brought to investment institutions, and how does Huachuang capital deal with them? How do you judge the 2020 venture capital hot track?

Xiong Weiming: The challenge for investment institutions is actually raising capital. Because investments are fast and slow, and you're GONNA miss them. I don't think it's the worst thing to miss out on a project, but the key is to have your own pace of fundraising.

Previously, the entire Chinese investment industry had already experienced a food shortage in 2018, and is now gradually recovering in the supply of RMB, but this is actually not an institutional recovery, but a policy-oriented recovery, this is actually the biggest challenge for the Chinese market.

In this case, fundraising should definitely have its own rhythm. We were lucky enough to have done the fundraising in 2018, so we're still investing the money we've raised over the last 18 years.

Last year, I did about 20 projects. For us, the speed is half of what it was before. I think the whole venture business will be slower this year, maybe only six or seven projects in total.

In 2020, we will continue to focus on core technologies, cutting edge technologies and corporate IT, and continue to push aggressively in this market.

Every new field has a bubble

Burning Finance and Economics: In the last two years, AI industry has not kept pace with the development of the outside world's expectations, "AI bubble burst theory" is very clamorous, how do you look at this reality? How do you think AI enterprises should respond to the current challenges?

Xiong Weiming: the development of AI is far from the outside world's expectations. In our circles, you're right when you say the AI bubble burst.

I remember when Baidu was looking for driverless and AI talent, and if you were willing to go back to China from Silicon Valley, you could get a 15% salary increase for the same level of employees, which was actually a bit of a bubble. But like a Cappuccino, it doesn't taste good without the foam. So the bubble has worked. It has made some people who used to be expensive to start a business or have high mobile costs, more willing to move to China and join Chinese start-ups or big companies. Now there are more and more people in the AI field.

It's kind of like in 2000, when there was no software talent. Computer science graduates from Chinese universities couldn't do direct business software at all, which was difficult for both individuals and businesses. So there was a software boom, too, which created a software talent bubble.

Every time a new field appears, we will find that there is still a long way to go for the relevant talent training.

Fuel Finance: In the fight against the epidemic process, there are some AI-related applications more eye-catching, which are you most concerned about? Will the demand for short-term outbreaks under epidemic conditions be sustainable in the future? WHAT AI related tracks can be focused on after an outbreak? WHAT SHOULD AI companies learn from the epidemic?

Xiong Weiming: we have some AI and retail companies, and we discovered some phenomena very early on. First, we found that identifying the customer needed to be linked to the ID card, so we wondered if we could make a face mask that could still identify the customer. AIBEE has made a technology that allows you to do facial recognition in a parking lot or a mall, even with a mask on.

Secondly, we're thinking about identity, and now we're thinking more about identifying with your physical signs, like, what's your temperature at 3:30 this afternoon, and what's your temperature when you show up at the mall? At this point, we changed what we used to call a consumer's shopping environment into a physical change, so we can determine whether the user is a potential patient or not. These are all places where using AI or automation or the Internet as a whole can help offline during an outbreak.

I don't think the AI track will be too affected by this outbreak.

Online is the best option

Self-driving is the future

Burning Finance and Economics: What were you doing during SARS in 2003? How does it feel now and then? After the epidemic, what industry's outbreak path can refer to that year SARS?

Xiong Weiming: In 2003, I started a bluetooth business. In 2000, we were watching the Internet of things, but it was too early. In 2004, I am doing Internet research coverage, mainly to Sina, Sohu, Netease three big companies. At that time, many companies had not yet gone public and felt that the overall economy would be much slower. At that time, there was no e-commerce, regional more obvious, only Beijing and Guangzhou close to the status of the city, but still free to go on the street.

After 2003, there was bird flu in 2004, two years of very challenging public health events. But I also clearly felt that 2004 was like a start. In fact, China's overall economy was not so good that year. Everyone had to discount when they evaluated Chinese companies. At that time, when we evaluated a big investor to want to invest in Netease, it mentions a 16% China discount. But in a remarkable turn of events in 2005, when China suddenly became the C of the brics, a premium market, the enthusiasm for investing in China was all there.

After 2003, e commerce, represented by Alibaba, slowly developed. At that time e commerce was very primitive. Taobao at that time was similar to today's Doddo. The average age of Internet users was about twenty-five or six years old, people don't have any money. So in the development of E-commerce, there are always some intergenerational and regional characteristics.

Alibaba, meanwhile, has grown from a valuation of $2 BILLION IN 2005 to $500 billion today. So I think online is the best claim in the whole field.

Burn the money: There was a self driving startup investment boom a few years back, but the big star startups were slow to grow, and even had a lot of sticky problems. Do you think there will be a big breakthrough in the self-driving industry in the next five years? Where is the current bottleneck? What type of player will have a better chance in the future?

Xiong Weiming: the other day, we saw pony get 400 million US dollars investment from Toyota. I think it is a strong shot in the arm for the industry.

China's autonomous driving has always been in the second tier, and it's worth noting that the United States'big business is no weaker than Internet companies like Google in the area of autonomous driving. If you look at where Fote and GM are investing, they're both investing heavily in driverless cars.

But in the field of automatic driving, China's host factory investment is still relatively small, facing a great challenge. Historically, China's first civilian car factory was built in 1985 by SAIC and Volkswagen.

From the beginning of the unknown to the mid-late 1990s with financial support, China's personal car has gradually developed into a large industry, today China has become the largest new car market. In fact, China's mainframe factories are all the way up, has not yet experienced the same large-scale merger as the United States.

In the United States, where self driving has evolved from Ford, founded in 1903, to Tesla, the challenge in China, where driverless is the equivalent of a fish swimming in water rapidly becoming a human walking on the ground, is enormous.

Electric cars are another challenge. There are a lot of changes to look forward to in electric cars, but the catfish may well come back to power plants, bringing them closer to the cutting edge.

In the future I think whether it's going to be L3, L4 in your car, or eventually it's going to be a fleet of cars, it's going to be a utility, self-driving is certainly an integral part of the entire auto industry.

At present, the main engine factory in the field of automatic driving is not a big investment. But I think if we don't get into it now, we might not have a ticket in the future. I think we can refer to the impact of the Xiaomi phone on the whole mobile phone chain, this wave of electric cars plus self-driving may have some impact on the Chinese mainframe factory.
